## Personal blog for Kyle Werner

Personal blog at [wernull.com](https://wernull.com) — tube amplifiers and tech.
Built with Jekyll 4, hosted on AWS S3 + CloudFront.

Local development runs in **Docker** so the native toolchain (Ruby + libvips
for responsive images) doesn't need to be installed or maintained on the host.

### Dev server (Docker)

```bash
docker compose up            # http://localhost:4000 (live-reload enabled)
docker compose up --build    # rebuild the image after changing the Gemfile
docker compose down          # stop
```

The project directory is bind-mounted, so edits to posts, styles, and layouts
reload automatically.

### New post

```bash
docker compose run --rm jekyll rake new_post['Post Title']
```

### Production build

```bash
docker compose run --rm -e JEKYLL_ENV=production jekyll bundle exec jekyll build
```

Output is written to `public/` on the host.

## Deploy

```bash
bash deploy.sh
```

`deploy.sh` builds the site in Docker, then uses the host AWS CLI (profile
`wernull`) to sync `public/` to `s3://wernull.com` and invalidate the two
CloudFront distributions. AWS credentials stay on the host and never enter the
container.

---

### Notes

- First `docker compose up` builds the image (installs Ruby gems + libvips);
  subsequent runs are fast.
- Ports: `4000` (site), `35729` (live-reload).
- `Gemfile.lock` includes Linux platforms (`x86_64-linux`, `aarch64-linux`) so
  bundler resolves correctly inside the container.
